# Research Canon — project adapter seam

This is the **one file `rasa.module.research` does not decide for you.** It
holds the three things that genuinely vary per project. It is **project-owned**:
seeded once at install and never overwritten on Element upgrade. Fill it in.

The portable discipline (the topic structure, the lifecycle, the three-layer
cross-reference model) lives in `.claude/research-rules.md` and refreshes on
upgrade. This seam is where *your project's* specifics go. The `/research`,
`/link`, and `/xref` skills read this file; `/research conclude` **hard-stops**
if `promotion_target` below is empty.

---

## 1. `research_root`

Where topic folders and `INDEX.md` live, relative to the project root.

    research_root: research/

<!-- Default `research/`. Change only if your project keeps investigations
     elsewhere (e.g. `docs/research/`, `notes/investigations/`). -->

---

## 2. `tags` — the taxonomy

The controlled vocabulary of topic tags for this project. `/link` and
`/research` draw tags only from this list; `/xref` matches on it. Keep it
small and real — tags are for *matching across topics*, so a tag that only
ever applies to one topic earns nothing.

    tags:
      # - <tag>            # <one-line meaning>

<!-- Fill with YOUR project's subjects. Illustrative sets (delete these):
     software:  [architecture, api, security, performance, tooling, protocol]
     legal:     [statute, case-law, contract, regulatory, precedent]
     health:    [pathway, guideline, pharmacology, diagnostics, outcomes]
     physics:   [symmetry, spin, measurement, spectral, parity, lattice]
     writing:   [character, plot, world, voice, period, structure]
     A tag not in this list is a deliberate taxonomy change — add it here
     first, don't sprinkle ad-hoc tags the matcher can't rely on. -->

---

## 3. `promotion_target` — where a concluded finding graduates

**Required for `/research conclude`.** When a topic concludes, its findings
graduate out of the research workspace into your project's durable layer.
Name that target here. Until this is set, `/research conclude` refuses to run
(guessing where a finding becomes durable is the one inference the module
won't make).

    promotion_target:
      # kind:   <notes-decision | domain-content | spec-or-rule | canon | other>
      # path:   <where it lands, e.g. notes/DECISIONS.md, content/, canon/…>
      # note:   <anything the conclude step should know>

<!-- Common targets (pick what fits; delete the rest):

  # A rasa.module.notes decision — the most common, cleanest hand-off.
  # Research answers "what did we find?"; notes records "so we decided X".
  promotion_target:
    kind: notes-decision
    path: notes/DECISIONS.md

  # Reference material the domain ships.
  promotion_target:
    kind: domain-content
    path: content/

  # A rule that changes how work is done.
  promotion_target:
    kind: spec-or-rule
    path: CLAUDE.md
-->

---

## 4. `promotion_criteria` — when a topic is ready to conclude (optional)

Overrides the default. Absent an override, `/research conclude` uses:
*the driving question has a stable, evidenced answer, and something depends on
it.*

    promotion_criteria:
      # - <your project's bar for concluding a topic>

<!-- Use this to encode a hard gate. Example (this workspace): a finding may
     not be promoted to canon until a canon *task* exists — so conclude must
     refuse and point at the task workflow. Encode that here:
     promotion_criteria:
       - Promotion to canon/ requires an open canon task first (see canon/tasks/).
-->

---

## 5. Sibling modules present (optional)

If these are mounted, the skills use them; if not, they degrade gracefully.
Note which are present so `conclude` and logging know what's available.

    siblings:
      notes:  <present | absent>    # promotion target for concluded findings
      tasks:  <present | absent>    # topics ↔ TASK-NNN cross-links
      ingest: <present | absent>    # kernel similarity-recall (memory_store)
      jobs:   <present | absent>    # scheduled dormant-topic review
